  "reasoning": "Let me fetch the specific articles with polling/abstention data and the historical INSEE data.Let me search for more specific polling data on voter intention for the 2026 elections and fetch the articles with relevant predictions.Now let me save my research findings and check prediction markets.Now let me run quantitative analysis and check prediction markets.Now let me write the meta-reflection and finalize.Based on my analysis, here's the summary of my forecast:\n\n**Historical trend**: Municipal election abstention has risen steadily from 21.6% (1983) to 36.5% (2014), with a decelerating rate of ~1.4pp/cycle by 2014. The 2020 result (55.3%) was a COVID anomaly. Trend extrapolation to 2026 gives ~38-42%.\n\n**Key factors**:\n- **No COVID**: Seniors return, fear removed → strong downward pressure from 2020 levels\n- **Political disaffection**: Post-2024 dissolution, low trust in national politics → upward pressure above pre-COVID trend\n- **Competitive races**: Paris, Marseille, Lyon, Bordeaux all contested → supports turnout\n- **Polling**: 60% \"certain to vote\" (IFOP Nov 2025), 69% interested (OpinionWay Jan 2026) → suggests ~38-42% abstention range\n- **Structural voting changes**: New proportional list system for all communes → uncertain effect\n- **Expert view** (Ifop's Dabi): \"Certainly better than 2020, but hard to project\"\n\n**Cross-checks converge**: European election gap method → 38-41%; polling → ~34-40%; trend models → 38-43%.\n\nMy Monte Carlo simulation (100k runs, 5 weighted scenarios) produces a median of ~42%, reflecting the pre-COVID trend plus modest uplift from political disaffection.",
